\PS. Dan was asking:

\Is "un cuadro" the right term for "a box"? Google almost always says, "una caja".
\The technically correct (but longer and accented) term is probably "un rectángulo".
\We used "box" because it was easier to type and less mathematical (and thus more friendly for kids) than "rectangle".
\In the SAL we can use any (or all) of them. Your choice.
I like all of them:
caja: common word
cuadro: more technical
rectángulo: pretty common and technical word

You two have good intuition.

\PPS. In case you missed it above, I need a rule like:

\I think I can fix this in the English/Spanish SAL if you can give me a rule like:
\"a" followed by "la" or __ or __ or __ is a preposition; while "a" followed by anything else is an English article
I repeat that you are a clever man.

The rule that you guess I find it correct for our purposes, that "a" followed by definite article could be treated as an English preposition:

a + la + fem. noun
a + el + masc. noun -> al + masc. noun

Contraction "al" from "a+el", similar to "del=de+el".
Old Spanish use "a el" but we read it as well as "al".

I didn't evaluate if "a" followed by indefinite article would be treated as an English preposition:

a + una + fem. noun
a + un + masc. noun

Un abrazo para los dos y felicitaciones al hábil Dan.

Pablo el lenguaraz.
